@nicolaskruchten d3's geo functions are where these weird characters come from, it uses greek letters in its source code for angles in the projections. d3v4 [converts all its source code to ASCII](https://github.com/d3/d3/blob/master/CHANGES.md#other-global-changes):

> To the consternation of some users, 3.x employed Unicode variable names such as Î», Ï†, Ï„ and Ï€ for a concise representation of mathematical operations. A downside of this approach was that a SyntaxError would occur if you loaded the non-minified D3 using ISO-8859-1 instead of UTF-8. 3.x also used Unicode string literals, such as the SI-prefix Âµ for 1e-6. 4.0 uses only ASCII variable names and ASCII string literals (see rollup-plugin-ascii), avoiding encoding problems.

It seems like this PR, while a very good hypothesis, doesn't solve whatever the underlying problem is. Let me take a look at #5112 again, that seems to me a more promising approach to get rid of this randomly-recurring issue permanently.

